9.Define ui5.yaml file and purpose
In SAPUI5, the ui5.yaml file is the central configuration file for the UI5 Tooling (now also known as UI5 CLI). It defines how your project—whether an application or a library—is built, served, and deployed.
ui5.yaml vs. manifest.json [1]
It is important to distinguish between these two configuration files:
•	ui5.yaml: Configures the development environment and build process (local server, CLI tools, proxies).
•	manifest.json: Configures the application runtime (routing, data models, and UI components)
Purpose and Key Functions
The ui5.yaml file acts as the "instruction manual" for the UI5 Command Line Interface (CLI), enabling several critical development tasks:
•	Project Metadata: It identifies the project type (e.g., application or library) and gives it a unique name.
•	Framework Management: You specify which framework to use (SAPUI5 or OpenUI5) and the exact version required for development.
•	Local Server Configuration: It configures the local development web server, including routes and custom middlewares.
•	Dependency Declaration: It lists the UI5 libraries (like sap.m or sap.ui.core) your project needs so the tooling can resolve them automatically.
•	Custom Middleware & Proxies: It allows you to set up tools like the fiori-tools-proxy to connect your local app to a backend OData service while bypassing cross-origin (CORS) issues.
•	Build Behavior: It controls how the application is packaged for deployment, such as creating a preload file to improve loading performance. [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7]

