13.Can we run the app without manifest.json file.
Yes, technically you can run a SAPUI5 application without a manifest.json file, but it is not recommended for modern Fiori development and is strictly required for certain deployment scenarios.
How it Works
In older versions of SAPUI5 or for very simple standalone apps, you can define your application's configuration directly in the index.html (via data-sap-ui-resourceroots) and the Component.js file. [1, 2, 3]
•	Manual Configuration: Without the manifest, you must manually instantiate models (like OData or i18n) and define routing rules within the init function of your Component.js.
•	Standalone Only: These apps generally run only as standalone web pages using an index.html file

14.How we can run the app in local.
Running a custom SAP Fiori application locally is primarily achieved using Visual Studio Code (VS Code) with the SAP Fiori tools extension pack and Node.js. The process involves creating a local development server, configuring ui5.yaml to connect to SAP systems, and using npm start to run the app in a browser for rapid development.
Key Methods for Local Fiori App Development
•	VS Code + Fiori Tools: Use the ">Fiori: Open Application Generator" in VS Code to create or configure projects, ensuring you set "Data Source" to a connected system or local file for development.
•	Running the Application: Use the terminal to run npm start or ui5 serve to initiate a local development server.
•	Connecting to Data: Configure the ui5-local.yaml file to use destinations or directly connect to a remote OData service, allowing local code to pull live data.
•	Local Sandbox: For testing, you can create a Sandbox.html file to run the app within a local launchpad shell, which simulates the Fiori container.

